---
title: Confit Duck Curry.
description: Add a little bit of luxury to your curry night with this richly spiced decadent duck curry. The strong, gamey flavour of duck is mellowed beautifully by an array of spices, with cooling yoghurt giving it a lovely creaminess. Served alongside ‘Cav Aloo’ (Mimi’s take on sag aloo, using cavolo nero instead of spinach) and topped with nigella seeds and fresh coriander for a show stopping finish, we’ve got bets on that this curry is about to become your household hero.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/confit-duck-curry-36827e18-7f1c5a08.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/confit-duck-curry-5aabcde630006c156d408471-a194b24e.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/confit-duck-curry-5aabcde630006c156d408471
author: Mimi Morley
servings: 2
course: main course
time required: 40 minutes
cuisine: Indian
nutrition:
  calories: 802 kcal
  fat: 32 g
  saturated fat: 9 g
  carbohydrates: 64 g
  sugar: 14 g
  protein: 64 g
  sodium: 5 g
  serving size: 673
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Cut the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm chunks (no need
to peel!), pop on a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, the
@ground turmeric{2%tsp}, half the @nigella seeds{1%tsp} and a pinch of
@salt{pinch} and @black pepper{}. Toss to coat and roast on the top shelf of
your oven until crisp, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).
Halve then remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1}(halved and thinly sliced).
Roughly chop the @coriander{10%sprigs}(roughly chopped).

While the potatoes cook, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #saucepan{} on medium
heat. Add the shallot and pepper, stir and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Stir in the @North Indian style spice mix{1%tbsp} (use less if you don't like
heat). Cook for ~{1%minute}. Pour in the @water{100%ml}, the
@chicken stock powder{1} and the @tomato passata{1}. Stir to dissolve the stock
pot and simmer until thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, carefully peel the skin off the @confit duck legs{2}. Remove and
discard the skin, fat and grease. Pull the flesh off the bone and separate
into bite-sized chunks. Once the curry is thick, add the duck, stir and simmer
until piping hot, ~{4-5%minutes}.

When the potatoes are cooked, remove them from the oven and lay the
@chopped cavolo nero{100%g} on top of the potatoes. Drizzle with some
@olive oil{}, and season with @black pepper{}. Pop back into your oven and
roast until the cavolo nero is crispy, ~{5%minutes}.

Heat a #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil). Once hot, lay in one of the
@super soft tortillas with whole wheat{2} and cook until slightly charred, about
~{30%seconds} to ~{1%minute} on each side. Remove to a #plate{} and season with
a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{}. Repeat with the remaining tortillas.

> We make one tortilla per person but you have enough for more if you fancy!

Warm your curry through to ensure it is hot, then taste it and add @salt{} and
@black pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Spoon into #bowls{} with your cavolo
nero. Add a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and sprinkle a pinch of
the remaining nigella seeds on top of each. Scatter over the coriander and serve
with the tortillas to scoop everything up. Enjoy!